Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/hasParliamentaryAgreement
Object: The relationship between a parliamentary party and the participation of that party in an agreement.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/hasAssociation
Object: The relationship between a party within Parliament and the membership of the party outside Parliament.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/accepts
Object: The relationship between a person as a Member and a whipping of that person: the acceptance of a whip by a Member.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/Pact
Object: An agreement between two or more political parties.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/Sistership
Object: A relationship between political parties who have agreed to co-operate.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/ParliamentaryBloc
Object: A group of Members of Parliament named for the purposes of administration, for example: a parliamentary party, the bishops or Crossbenchers in the House of Lords.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/hasPact
Object: The relationship between a political party and the inclusion of that party within a pact.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/
Object: A model describing the whipping of a Member to a parliamentary party or the affiliation of a Member with a parliamentary bloc. A parliamentary bloc may be a parliamentary party, or may be a non-political group, for example: the Crossbenchers in the House of Lords.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/whippedTo
Object: The relationship between a whipping of a Member and a parliamentary party, for example: between the whipping of a Liberal Member and the parliamentary Liberal Party.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/ParliamentaryAgreement
Object: An agreement between two or more parliamentary parties to cooperate within Parliament, for example: a confidence and supply or coalition agreement.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/hasSistership
Object: The relationship between a political party and the participation of that party within a sistership.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/MemberWhipping
Object: The acceptance of a whip to a parliamentary party by a Member between two dates: the whip may be withdrawn by a party or declined by a Member.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/PoliticalParty
Object: A group registered with the Electoral Commission as a political party.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/Affiliation
Object: An affiliation to a parliamentary bloc held by a Member between two dates, for example: an affiliation to the Co-operative Party whilst accepting the whip of the Labour Party.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/ParliamentaryParty
Object: A group of Members of Parliament accepting a party whip.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-bloc/hasAffiliation
Object: The relationship between an affiliation of a Member and a parliamentary bloc, for example: between a affiliation of a Crossbencher and the Crossbenchers in the House of Lords.
